    "We then explore the complexity of various ethical problems based on consequentialism (Sect. 4), deontology (Sect.",
    "5), and virtue ethics (Sect. 6).",
    "The main aim is to elucidate the complexity associated with the problems themselves (e.g., due to uncertainty, combinatorics, strategic dynamics, and generality), the available resources (e.g., time, cognition, and domain knowledge), and the computational methods employed to tackle the problems (e.g., probability, logic, and learning).",
